    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="647"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d647">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.24/1450</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Director of the Bureau of the Budget</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smith</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-03">July 3,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Smith</hi>: The receipt is acknowledged of Mr.
                        Bailey’s<note n="81" xml:id="d647fn81">F. J. Bailey, Assistant Director of
                        the Bureau.</note> letter of June 18, 1941,<note n="82" xml:id="d647fn82"
                        >Not printed.</note> in which you request my opinion relative to H. J. Res.
                    189, a resolution “Requesting the President of the United States of America to
                    exercise the powers vested in him under section 6 of Public, Numbered 703,
                    Seventy-sixth Congress, to the end that no further shipments of petroleum or
                    petroleum products shall be made to Japan, and for other purposes”. You enclose
                    a copy of a report<note n="82" xml:id="d647fn1">Not printed.</note> which the
                    Secretary of War proposes to submit to the Chairman of the House Committee on
                    Military Affairs in regard to this matter. It is noted that the War Department
                    does not favor enactment of this proposed legislation.</p>
                <p>From the standpoint of foreign policy, I urge most strongly that the proposed
                    legislation not be enacted. I entirely concur in the reasons set forth in the
                    report which the Secretary of War proposes to submit to the House Committee on
                    Military Affairs.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sumner Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
